    "stac_version": "1.1.0",
    "description": "SST provides global sea surface temperature derived primarily from thermal infrared observations during daytime. Users apply SST to detect fronts and eddies, monitor marine heatwaves, drive ecosystem and habitat models (when paired with chlor_a, Kd_490, PAR), and provide boundary conditions for biogeochemical and climate analyses. Note that IR-based SST is sensitive to clouds, aerosols, and diurnal warming; for minimum diurnal effects, pair with NSST (nighttime SST) and refer to per-file flags before analysis.\n\n Geophysical variables in this suite include:\n\u2022 bias_sst \u2014 Sea Surface Temperature bias (\u00b0C)\n\u2022 flags_sst \u2014 Product-specific flags, Sea Surface Temperature (integer bitmask)\n\u2022 l2_flags \u2014 Level-2 Processing Flags (integer bitmask; see bit definitions)\n\u2022 qual_sst \u2014 Quality levels for Sea Surface Temperature (integer quality flag)\n\u2022 sst \u2014 Sea Surface Temperature (\u00b0C)\n\u2022 sstref \u2014 Sea Surface Temperature reference (\u00b0C)\n\u2022 stdv_sst \u2014 Sea Surface Temperature standard deviation (\u00b0C)\n",
